AbleChildAfrica has been working for 4 years now with a wider remit than the former USDC UK - supporting a range of partners working on innovative solutions to change the lives of disabled children in Africa. Our 2007-2012 strategy has seen us achieving our goal of developing five partnerships accross 3 countries and finding a way to develop a positive approach to partnership with organisations working with disabled children and youth. We are coming to the end of our intial five year strategy and would like this grant to support the development of our next strategic plan consolidating what has been achieved to date and capitalising on our core mission going forward. In addition we would like support in two areas which we think will be key in that strategy - 1. the development of a well considered mechanism through which we can support mainstream development providers working with children to make their programmes and organisations inclusive and 2. the strengthening of our partnership network enabling it to grow and develop cross-network learning which we believe has significant benefits but which is difficult to fund from other sources.

According to UNESCO, under two-thirds of adults in Malawi can read. This project aims to improve children's literacy and numeracy skills in the infant years of primary school in Malawi. Every week, children are taken through a number of topics linked to the curriculum. Teachers are trained to support this work and adapt their own teaching practice in the classroom. Small classrooms are built for each school, allowing smaller classes. This work has demonstrated significant gain in an eight week period for some children.

Adama is a railway transit town with a population of 127,842 (7-18 population is 63,352) of which over 2000 are children living off on/the the streets. The railway is a big attraction for business opportunities and many people have fallen into the trap of chasing dreams which have resulted in poor livelihoods. Children have either been born or migrated to this place in search of opportunities and many are living tough lives eking a living as porters, casual workers, sex workers simply living on the streets. The rights of these children are trampled upon every day and they have limited safety nets. This application will undertake a research into the context of the street children in the country and Adama in particular, the extent of the problem, the nature of the problem, the available opportunities for addressing the problems. It will map out existing services and identify the key stakeholders. The result will be a greater understanding of the situation of street children in Adama, the opportunities there are to address any identified issues, and design of appropriate interventions. Implementation of follow-on programmes should ensure the upholding of the rights of street children, and ensuring a brighter future for them.

African Initiatives is a social justice organisation working in Ghana and Tanzania. It also undertakes global education in the UK. It works with partners to empower communities to claim their rights. African Initiatives provides partners with capacity building in key areas. In 2011, with assistance from Comic Relief, INTRAC, KPMG and DFID, the organisation carried out a series of self-assessments which produced recommendations for governance, strategy, finance, fundraising, monitoring and advocacy work. African Initiatives wishes to determine its future direction; strategic objectives and indicators need to be set and monitored over the next five years. Governance systems require strengthening as the organisation grows, seeks out new partnerships and invests in key positions for fundraising and marketing. As income from institutional grants grows it will be important to modify and align African Initiative's financial management systems too.

African women play a very small role in their countries' technological and digital industries. Efforts to address this have focused on short-term needs rather than building technological skills and knowledge. This project encourages women in Ghana to use digital technology tools to develop everyday solutions to the problems they and their peers face. It aims to increase the number of women with IT skills and the number that are able to build a career in technology, either as expert programmers or as founders of technology related start-ups. This includes a coding bootcamp, and an accelerator programme for those who develop viable ideas for technological solutions.

After a long civil war, farmers in the Casamance, Senegal, are working to develop the economy and have wild fruits to sell. This project helps thousands of farmers to organise a marketing association, to set up collection centres and to care for their land and wild forests better. Female farmers are directly supported so they can meet, learn new skills and ensure they are actively represented in the new organisations. Two Senegalese social enterprises are contributing to the project and provide the link to European markets. In addition, a UK Fair Trade juice pioneer is building a Fair Trade brand and a means of distribution for these products.

Agriculture remains the main source of income for 70% of rural Zimbabwe. However, mass movement to cities has reduced agricultural knowledge and labour, with many households forced to barter for food. Garden Africa supports farmers to produce more crops without dependence on chemicals and to provide food for their families, with enough left over to sell. Locally based agricultural workers with links to each community are trained to support a shift from chemical to organic farming. The farmers are supported to develop farmer associations to learn how to self-certify their products as organic. This is the first step towards a formal certification for trading with national and international markets. The associations also sell to local and national buyers. The project provides opportunities for local farmers to earn more money from their crops, and also informs the government and the general public on the benefits of growing and consuming organic products.

All too often children working or living on the streets spiral into conflict with authorities and the law. Many are unable to express themselves properly, because of trauma, disability or lack of any form of schooling. This may have been at the root of their leaving home or it may be what stops them returning. This project builds local expertise to identify these problems and then works with schools and caring organisations to overcome them. This helps children to protect themselves from abuse and avoid getting into trouble and also helps them to reintegrate with their communities. In the process teachers are helped to ensure all their children can learn in less disruptive and hence more productive classrooms.

Although it can be prevented and treated, diarrhoea is responsible for 15,000 deaths of Zambian children each year. However, a new vaccine for rotavirus that can prevent up to one-third of all diarrhoeal deaths is now available. This project will help to reduce diarrhoeal illness and deaths of children using an integrated approach. ARK will provide rotavirus vaccines for children in the four districts of Lusaka Province, covering about one-sixth of Zambia''s total population. They will train health workers to better manage children with diarrhoea, help make drugs to treat diarrhoea more available in the public and private sectors and help families and communities learn to prevent and treat the condition. The project is linked to a research programme to show the effects of this holistic approach on child deaths. Partners of ARK are working with government to create and document a model diarrhoea control programme that can be expanded to other parts of the country. This will result in fewer diarrhoeal illnesses and deaths of children under-five in Zambia.

60% of young people in Sierra Leone are unemployed or underemployed. Many had their education disrupted by civil war. Lack of appropriate skills in the labour force slows the country's development and high quality, affordable vocational training is not readily available in Freetown. This project trains young men and women in life skills and vocational courses matched to employer demand. It offers business training and mentorship to young entrepreneurs, facilitates work placements and employment by making connections with companies, and raises revenue by charging firms for recruitment and in-house employee training. The project also helps young people improve their livelihoods and creates a better environment for employment.
